  "prompt": "How much money in charitable donations can a person deduct from his/her taxes before being taxed on his/her donations in the US?",
  "response": "In the United States, the amount of charitable donations a taxpayer can deduct from their taxable income depends on several factors, including the taxpayer's filing status, income level, and the type of charitable organization receiving the donation. \n\nFor tax year 2023, individuals who itemize their deductions can generally deduct:\n\n1. **Cash Donations**: Up to 60% of their adjusted gross income (AGI) for contributions made to public charities and certain private foundations.\n   \n2. **Donation of Property**: Generally, taxpayers can deduct the fair market value of property donations (e.g., stocks, real estate) at the time of the donation. The deduction limit can vary depending on the type of property and the charity.\n\n3. **Donations of Appreciated Assets**: If the donation is appreciated property (like stocks held for more than a year), taxpayers may be able to deduct the fair market value up to 30% of their AGI.\n\nIf a taxpayer's total charitable contributions exceed these limits in a given year, they may carry forward the excess amount and deduct it in future tax years (up to five years).\n\nIt\u2019s important to keep in mind that these rules can change, and there may be additional considerations based on individual circumstances. Therefore, consulting with a tax professional or accountant is advisable for personalized guidance.",
